patch:
diff --git a/llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp b/llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp
index b821da03c16e..6e1f97e56651 100644
--- a/llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp
+++ b/llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp
@@ -2965,6 +2965,51 @@ void InnerLoopVectorizer::fixVectorizedLoop(VPTransformState &State,
                    getOrCreateVectorTripCount(VectorLoop->getLoopPreheader()),
                    IVEndValues[Entry.first], LoopMiddleBlock,
                    VectorLoop->getHeader(), Plan, State);
+
+    // Also repair pre-existing PHI nodes in the unique exit block that are not
+    // modeled as live-outs by VPlan. These may be simple passthrough PHIs of
+    // loop-invariant values and were created before vectorization. After adding
+    // the edge from LoopMiddleBlock to the exit, such PHIs must gain an incoming
+    // value for the new predecessor (or have their single incoming edge's block
+    // updated) to preserve IR validity.
+    if (LoopExitBlock) {
+      SmallVector<BasicBlock *, 4> Preds(predecessors(LoopExitBlock));
+      for (PHINode &PN : LoopExitBlock->phis()) {
+        // Fast path: single incoming edge which is no longer a predecessor and
+        // there is exactly one current predecessor (the middle block). Redirect.
+        if (PN.getNumIncomingValues() == 1) {
+          BasicBlock *IncBB = PN.getIncomingBlock(0);
+          if (!llvm::is_contained(Preds, IncBB) && Preds.size() == 1) {
+            PN.setIncomingBlock(0, Preds[0]);
+            continue;
+          }
+        }
+        // Ensure PHI has incoming for every predecessor.
+        for (BasicBlock *PredBB : Preds) {
+          if (PN.getBasicBlockIndex(PredBB) != -1)
+            continue; // Already has incoming.
+          // Reuse an existing loop-invariant incoming value if possible.
+          Value *IncomingV = nullptr;
+          for (unsigned I = 0, E = PN.getNumIncomingValues(); I < E; ++I) {
+            Value *Cand = PN.getIncomingValue(I);
+            if (OrigLoop->isLoopInvariant(Cand)) { IncomingV = Cand; break; }
+          }
+          if (!IncomingV && PN.getNumIncomingValues() > 0)
+            IncomingV = PN.getIncomingValue(0);
+          if (!IncomingV)
+            continue; // Defensive: shouldn't happen.
+          PN.addIncoming(IncomingV, PredBB);
+        }
+        // Remove incoming edges from blocks that are no longer predecessors.
+        for (unsigned I = 0; I < PN.getNumIncomingValues(); ++I) {
+          BasicBlock *IncBB = PN.getIncomingBlock(I);
+          if (!llvm::is_contained(Preds, IncBB)) {
+            PN.removeIncomingValue(I, /*DeletePHIIfEmpty=*/false);
+            --I; // Re-check current index after removal.
+          }
+        }
+      }
+    }
   }

   // Fix live-out phis not already fixed earlier.

reason_thou:
1. Understanding the Issue:
The crash is an IR verification failure after loop vectorization. The verifier reports: "PHINode should have one entry for each predecessor of its parent basic block! %use = phi i64 [ %start2, %for.body ]". This indicates the loop-vectorizer mutated the CFG such that the exit block now has a different predecessor set than before, but an existing PHI (%use) was not updated to reflect the new predecessors. The reproducer has a single-exit loop with a trivial loop-invariant PHI in the exit block. After vectorization, a new predecessor (the 'middle block') is added (when no scalar epilogue is required), but the PHI still lists the original predecessor (which may no longer be a predecessor or is insufficient), triggering the assertion.

2. Analyzing opt's Log:
The log shows the failure occurs at the final verification in LoopVectorizePass::processLoop right after executing the vectorization plan. No other diagnostics are emitted. ScalarEvolution output is normal. The first transformation point (executePlan + subsequent fix-up) completes and then verification fails at line 10247. Thus the IR was left in an inconsistent state by earlier transformation code, particularly inside executePlan / fixVectorizedLoop.

3. Root Cause Analysis:
In executePlan, the skeleton is created via InnerLoopVectorizer::createVectorizedLoopSkeleton, which (if a scalar epilogue is NOT required) later results in an edge from the newly created 'middle block' directly to the loop's unique exit block (see the diagram in comments). When this optional edge is inserted, existing PHIs in the exit block must gain incoming values for the new predecessor. fixVectorizedLoop only adjusts:
- Induction variable users (fixupIVUsers)
- Live-outs tracked in VPlan (Plan.getLiveOuts())
It does NOT generically update pre-existing PHIs in the exit block that are loop-invariant pass-throughs (like %use). Therefore, when the predecessor set changes, those PHIs are stale. In the specific reproducer the loop-invariant value 'start2' is passed through a PHI with a single incoming from the original loop latch. After vectorization without scalar epilogue, the exit block's sole predecessor may become the middle block (or gains an additional predecessor), and the PHI lacks the required incoming for that predecessor, violating IR invariants.

4. Proposed Edit Points(s):
File: llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp
Location: Inside InnerLoopVectorizer::fixVectorizedLoop, right after finishing induction variable fix-ups (after the closing brace of the 'else' block that handles the case where the middle block edge exists) and before handling live-outs.
Edit lines 2968-2968 (replace the single '}' line with augmented logic):
Reasoning: This is the minimal, localized place where we already know whether the middle block->exit edge exists (i.e. requiresScalarEpilogue(VF.isVector()) is false). We add a repair loop that ensures every PHI in the exit block has an incoming value for the new predecessor. Special handling is added for the case where the PHI previously had only one incoming (simple passthrough) and the predecessor changed; we update the block rather than adding a second incoming. Otherwise we add an incoming value (re-using a loop-invariant existing incoming if possible).
Patch concept:
Replace line 2968:
    }
with:
    }
    // Fix missing incoming edges for existing exit-block PHIs after adding
    // the edge from LoopMiddleBlock to LoopExitBlock when no scalar epilogue
    // is required. Some pre-existing PHIs (e.g. trivial loop-invariant passthrough
    // PHIs) are not modeled in VPlan live-outs and were never updated.
    if (!Cost->requiresScalarEpilogue(VF.isVector()) && LoopExitBlock) {
      for (PHINode &PN : LoopExitBlock->phis()) {
        // Case 1: PHI had a single incoming edge from the old predecessor,
        // but now the only predecessor is LoopMiddleBlock. Update block.
        if (PN.getNumIncomingValues() == 1 &&
            PN.getBasicBlockIndex(LoopMiddleBlock) == -1) {
          // If the old incoming block is no longer a predecessor, just redirect.
          BasicBlock *OnlyPred = *pred_begin(LoopExitBlock);
          if (OnlyPred == LoopMiddleBlock) {
            PN.setIncomingBlock(0, LoopMiddleBlock);
            continue;
          }
        }
        // Case 2: Middle block is a new predecessor but PHI lacks an incoming.
        if (PN.getBasicBlockIndex(LoopMiddleBlock) == -1) {
          Value *V = nullptr;
          // Prefer a loop-invariant existing incoming value.
          for (unsigned I = 0; I < PN.getNumIncomingValues(); ++I) {
            Value *IncV = PN.getIncomingValue(I);
            if (OrigLoop->isLoopInvariant(IncV)) { V = IncV; break; }
          }
            if (!V && PN.getNumIncomingValues() > 0)
              V = PN.getIncomingValue(0);
          if (V)
            PN.addIncoming(V, LoopMiddleBlock);
        }
      }
    }

5. Conclusion:
The failure stems from not updating pre-existing exit-block PHIs after inserting a new predecessor when no scalar epilogue is required. Adding a targeted fix in fixVectorizedLoop ensures all PHIs include an incoming for LoopMiddleBlock (or remap the single incoming) thus restoring IR consistency and preventing the assertion. This localized change maintains existing behavior for modeled live-outs and reductions and only repairs previously ignored trivial PHIs.

